      "writtenOn": "2019-09-11T14:02:16Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Naming conventions in Go are some of the strangest to get used to (IMO), but once you understand them, things are very elegant. \n\nhttps://golang.org/doc/effective_go.html#package-names\n\n\"The importer of a package will use the name to refer to its contents, so exported names in the package can use that fact to avoid stutter. [...] For instance, the buffered reader type in the bufio package is called Reader, not BufReader, because users see it as bufio.Reader, which is a clear, concise name.\"\n\nsince our package name is goldpushk (a fine package name), all clients will be referring to these types as\ngoldpushk.GoldInstance when they could just say goldpushk.Instance\n\nSo, drop Gold from all exported names in this package.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 8,
        "startChar": 5,
        "endLine": 8,
        "endChar": 17
      },
      "revId": "2f3bd08c0981991789d64e0e29480c64d100524b",
